{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529482"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14420"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14420"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.81,0.01,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7115"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"9772"},{"type":"tags","id":"12914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance following what she describes as a severe panic attack at work. She reports six weeks of increasing anxiety with frequent episodes of palpitations, sweating, and feeling like she is \u0027going crazy\u0027. She has been sleeping only three hours per night and feels constantly restless. She was previously well with no psychiatric history but recently started seeing a psychologist for anxiety. She takes no regular medications. Her older sister has bipolar disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed and is hyperventilating. Her pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 145/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Her hands are warm and slightly tremulous. She has lost 4 kg despite eating more than usual. Cardiorespiratory examination is normal except for the tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe alprazolam for panic disorder","Order thyroid function tests","Commence olanzapine for possible mania","Arrange urgent psychiatric assessment","Start propranolol for anxiety symptoms"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a diagnostic challenge as the predominant symptoms suggest a primary anxiety or panic disorder, particularly given the family history of psychiatric illness. However, several subtle features point toward hyperthyroidism as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. The combination of persistent anxiety, weight loss despite increased appetite, tachycardia, tremor, and warm peripheries suggests thyroid dysfunction. While the psychiatric symptoms are prominent, the physical signs cannot be explained by anxiety alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing alprazolam\u003C/strong\u003E might provide temporary symptomatic relief but would mask the underlying endocrine disorder. Benzodiazepines should be avoided until the cause of symptoms is established, particularly as thyroid dysfunction can make patients more sensitive to their effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting olanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without clear evidence of mania. While the patient shows signs of agitation and sleep disturbance, these can be explained by thyroid dysfunction, and antipsychotics may complicate the clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging urgent psychiatric assessment\u003C/strong\u003E before excluding medical causes would delay appropriate treatment. The presence of physical signs and autonomic symptoms suggests this is not a primary psychiatric presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting propranolol\u003C/strong\u003E might improve some symptoms (particularly tachycardia and tremor) but would not address the underlying cause. While beta-blockers are often used in thyroid storm, they should not be initiated before thyroid function is assessed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case emphasizes the importance of maintaining a high index of suspicion for medical causes of psychiatric symptoms, particularly when autonomic features are present. Thyroid dysfunction can present primarily with psychological symptoms, and the physical signs may be subtle. The combination of anxiety, weight loss despite increased appetite, and autonomic symptoms should always prompt consideration of hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyperthyroidism can present with severe anxiety and panic attacks that may initially be mistaken for primary psychiatric disorders.","Physical signs of thyroid dysfunction may be subtle and require careful examination, especially in younger patients.","The combination of anxiety, weight loss, and autonomic symptoms should prompt consideration of endocrine causes."],"references":["Campbell K, Doogue M. Evaluating and managing patients with thyrotoxicosis. Australian family physician. 2012 Aug;41(8):564-72."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14420"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T09:59:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T10:01:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7115"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57939"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro